            . I live with Mr. Dawson, the corner of Monmouth street. Three men came to the shop on Saturday-night the 20th of May; I believe Lewis and Muggleton are two of them; I am sure the cloaths they have on, are what they bought of me; they told me, their master was going out of town, and had not time to get their cloaths made; they had a portmanteau or saddle bag with them; the cloaths they put into it; the lace of the livery are very remarkable, and the brown coat and the buttons upon it arevery remarkable.</p>
               <p>Cross Examination.</p>
               <p>Q. Do you swear to the persons of these men?</p>
               <p>Gardner. No, I think the cloaths they have on, are the same cloaths they had of me. I saw them at Sir 
               <persName id="t17750712-49-person443">
                  John
                   Fielding
               <interp inst="t17750712-49-person443" type="surname" value="Fielding"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17750712-49-person443" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17750712-49-person443" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            's, and I believe them to be the same.</p>
               <p>Q. What do you know the brown cloaths by?</p>
               <p>Gardner. By the buttons.</p>
               <p>Q. You say, it is a remarkable button on the brown coat.</p>
               <p>Gardner. Yes.</p>
               <p>Q. What is there to know the brown cloaths by but the buttons?</p>
               <p>
                  <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="177507120033"></xptr>Gardner. Nothing further than the cut sleeve and the sunk buttons.</p>
               <p>Q. Where were the buttons made?</p>
               <p>Gardner. I know not.</p>
               <p>Q. Where did you buy them?</p>
               <p>Gardner. I do not know.</p>
               <p>Q. When were the cloaths made?</p>
               <p>Gardner. The beginning of the season.</p>
               <p>Q. Was the Denmark cuff the running fashion the beginning of the season?</p>
               <p>Gardner. Yes.</p>
               <p>Q. What do you know the livery by?</p>
               <p>Gardner. By the lace and the colour.</p>
               <p>Q. Did you never see a light coloured coat before?</p>
               <p>Gardner. Yes.</p>
               <p>Q. What sort of lace is it?</p>
               <p>Gardner. It is remarkable.</p>
               <p>Q. It is livery lace?</p>
               <p>Gardner. Yes.</p>
               <p>Q. How long has it been in fashion?</p>
               <p>Gardner. I do not know.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17750712-49-person444">
                  John
                   Swindill
               <interp inst="t17750712-49-person444" type="surname" value="Swindill"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17750712-49-person444" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17750712-49-person444" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live at the Goose and Hoop, at Moorgate. I am a post-boy, I know Lewis; he, and two others, came on a Sunday morning between one and two o'clock. I drove them to Barnet. Lewis paid me for the chaise.</p>
               <p>- Davis. I deal with Mr. Lowry, a watchmaker and silversmith, at Carlisle. On the 3d of June, I received a box of light gold from Mr. Lowry, and among it there were a chain and dial-plate, and the cases of a repeating watch (the watch cases were produced in court, and deposed to by the prosecutrix.) There were also a five guinea piece, and a two guinea piece.</p>
